    phoenician_orthography_phonology_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Merger of Gutturals</strong></td><td>Guttural consonants (like á¸¥ and Ê¿) merged phonetically in early Phoenician and were represented by the letter <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤‡</code> (á¸¤et).</td><td>The name á¸¤am is represented as <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤‡ğ¤Œ</code> (á¸¤M).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Merger of Interdentals</strong></td><td>Interdental sounds (like 'th' in 'thin' or 'then') disappeared and merged with nearby sibilants (Å¡, z, á¹£).</td><td>The word for "went" (Proto-Semitic *á¸ahaba) likely became <em>z-b-</em> in Phoenician, reflecting the 'dh' to 'z' shift.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Use of Waw and Yod for Long Vowels</strong></td><td>The letters <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤…</code> (w) and <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤‰</code> (y) are primarily used to indicate long vowels (like /Å«/, /Ä«/, /Å/, and /Ä“/).</td><td>The word 'År' (light): <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤€ğ¤…ğ¤“</code> ('WR).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_pronouns_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>3rd Person Singular Pronoun (he/she)</strong></td><td>The most common form for the 3rd person personal pronoun is <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤„ğ¤€</code> (h'), used for both masculine ('he') and feminine ('she').</td><td>"He is the god": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤„ğ¤€ ğ¤„ğ¤€ğ¤‹</code> (h' h'l).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Possessive Suffix (his)</strong></td><td>The possessive suffix for 3rd person singular masculine is <code>-w</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤…</code>) or <code>-h</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤„</code>) (in construct cases).</td><td>"His servant": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤ğ¤ƒğ¤…</code> ('bdw).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Object Suffix (them)</strong></td><td>The suffix for the 3rd person plural object is <code>-nm</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤Œ</code>) or <code>-m</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤Œ</code>).</td><td>"He blessed them": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤“ğ¤Šğ¤ğ¤Œ</code> (brknm).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_noun_adjective_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>No Case Endings</strong></td><td>Phoenician does not retain the three case endings (nominative, accusative, genitive) of Proto-Semitic. The function of a word is determined by its context in the sentence.</td><td><code class='phoenician'>ğ¤Œğ¤‹ğ¤Š</code> (mlk) can be a subject, object, or possessor, pronounced /malk/ in all cases.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Construct State</strong></td><td>The first noun in a possessive chain (the "construct") appears without the definite article (<code>h-</code>), while the article is attached to the second noun if it is definite.</td><td>"The well of the king": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤€ğ¤“ ğ¤„ğ¤Œğ¤‹ğ¤Š</code> (b'r hmlk).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Irregular Plurals</strong></td><td>There are cases where the masculine plural ends in <code>-t</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤•</code>), which is typically the feminine singular/plural ending.</td><td><em>mÄ«lakt</em> ("kingdoms" - a feminine plural).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_verb_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Nip'al Stem (Passive/Reflexive)</strong></td><td>This verb stem is formed by prefixing <code>n-</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤</code>) or <code>'n-</code> (<code class='phoenician'>ğ¤€ğ¤</code>) to the root and indicates a passive or reflexive action.</td><td>"He was saved/rescued" (Nip'al): <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤‘ğ¤‹</code> (ná¹£l).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Infinitive Absolute</strong></td><td>The infinitive absolute (often of the Qatol pattern) is used to emphasize a verb. Its form remains unchanged regardless of subject or tense.</td><td>"He surely blessed": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤“ğ¤Š ğ¤ğ¤“ğ¤Š</code> (brk brk).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Imperative Mood</strong></td><td>The masculine singular command form is derived from the imperfect stem (Yiqtol) without the pronominal prefix.</td><td>"Rule!": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤Œğ¤‹ğ¤Š</code> (mlk) (from <code>ymlk</code>).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
    phoenician_prepositions_particles_content: `<table><thead><tr><th>Rule</th><th>Description</th><th>Phoenician Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Conjunction "w-" (and)</strong></td><td>The letter <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤…</code> (w-) is used for "and" and is attached to the following word. It can also mean "then" in narrative sequences.</td><td>"and he": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤…ğ¤„ğ¤€</code> (wh').</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Preposition "l-" (to/for)</strong></td><td>The letter <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤‹</code> (l-) is used for "to," "for," or to indicate possession in a nominal construction.</td><td>"I had" (lit. "to me was"): <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤‹ğ¤‰ ğ¤Šğ¤</code> (ly kn).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Relative Pronoun</strong></td><td>The relative pronoun is <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤€ğ¤”</code> ('Å¡), meaning "which" or "that."</td><td>"The city that...": <code class='phoenician'>ğ¤ğ¤“ ğ¤€ğ¤”</code> ('r 'Å¡).</td></tr></tbody></table>`,
